The theoretical requirement that KR take values from 25 to 45 μM may reflect different densities of P2Y receptors on the microglia, since in the present theory KR depends on this density as well as on the dissociation of ATP from the receptors (see Theory section above, and also the following section). Polyclonal antibody labelling of P2Y12 (Fig. 7a) receptors indicated that these are localized in clusters of average diameter 0.45 \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}$\mu \mbox{m}$\end{document}, as are P2Y receptors on astrocytes [5] and smooth-muscle cells [30]. The density of P2Y12 receptors, measured over nine microglial cells, varied about four-fold (Fig. 7b). We suggest that P2Y12 receptors mediate the Ca2 +  wave propagation. Since in the present model KR values need to vary over at least a two-fold range, it may be that this variability is partly due to differences in P2Y12 receptor density.
