A quantitative analysis of Ca2 +  wave propagation in a lane, such as that shown in Fig. 8, gives the results summarised in Fig. 9. The peak amplitude of Ca2 +  in each microglial cell of the lane varied significantly both along the length and across the width of the lane (Fig. 9a). Normalizing the Ca2 +  to the largest amplitude observed at the site of initiation shows that many of the cells give a Ca2 +  amplitude that is less than 15% of the largest one (Fig. 9a). Using this as a cut-off for the ΔF/F value that would be observed experimentally (see Methods) gives a rate of decline of Ca2 +  with distance similar to that observed, from 100% to 20% over about 120 \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
